<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-03-31T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-03-31T07:00:00-05:00" n="916" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d916">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">361.1121 Pyk, Irena Teodozja/10:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-03-31T15:00:00+03:00">March 31,
                                    1941—3 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 4:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>636. As illustrating the difficulties inherent in obtaining the release
                            of any individual imprisoned in the Soviet Union, I have recently
                            learned from a reliable source that Molotov’s sister-in-law and
                            Vyshinski’s daughter, his only child, have been in jail for some months
                            during the past year.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>